crowdsourced_ids_results.rule_msg: ET INFO Observed Google DNS over HTTPS Domain (dns .google in TLS SNI)
crowdsourced_ids_results.rule_raw: alert tls $HOME_NET any -> $EXTERNAL_NET any (msg:"ET INFO Observed Google DNS over HTTPS Domain (dns .google in TLS SNI)"; flow:established,to_server; threshold: type both, track by_src, count 1, seconds 600; tls.sni; dotprefix; content:".dns.google"; endswith; reference:url,developers.google.com/speed/public-dns/docs/doh/; classtype:misc-activity; sid:2047866; rev:4; metadata:affected_product Any, attack_target Client_Endpoint, created_at 2022_02_07, deployment Perimeter, performance_impact Low, confidence High, signature_severity Informational, tag DoH, updated_at 2023_10_05, reviewed_at 2023_10_05, former_sid 2851058; target:src_ip;)

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis:
The technical analysis of the PDF's internal structure did not reveal any malicious components. No automatic execution triggers, JavaScript code, or network indicators were found. The file contains two stream objects with decoding errors, suggesting potential corruption or an unsupported format, but these anomalies are not considered malicious on their own.

However, the visual analysis of the document's content raises significant concerns. The file displays only a single, generic phrase, "Hello dear.", with a complete absence of any other text, images, sender identification, or context. This minimalist and impersonal presentation is highly uncharacteristic of legitimate correspondence.

While the file lacks a direct technical payload, its content is consistent with the initial stages of a social engineering or phishing attack designed to pique the recipient's curiosity and initiate a dialogue. The combination of a technically inert file with highly suspicious, context-free content justifies the final judgment.
